{
  "texts": [
    "End-users typically do not reason about privacy in the way quantified by, and people are known to struggle with reasoning about risks from low-probability events (Tversky & Kahneman, 1974).",
    "Recent work of Nanayakkara et al. (2023) developed and evaluated methods for explaining the probabilistic privacy guarantees to end-users: two that communicate the relative odds of various outcomes with and without the user's data, and one offering concrete examples of outputs sampled from DP mechanisms with the appropriate.",
    "Odds-based explanation methods were found to be more effective than output-based methods, as well as existing DP explanation methods that do not explicitly describe.",
    "This initial work suggests a promising path for future explanatory tools.",
    "Future work should extend this line of inquiry to both develop improved methods for communicating the privacy guarantees, as well as methods for evaluating efficacy of new methods."
  ]
}